daily_routine: Every morning at 4 AM, Anyu checks ice conditions from her kitchen
  window with binoculars her grandfather gave her, reading wind patterns and ice colors
  the way her ancestors did for millennia. She tests the ice thickness with her kakivak
  (fishing spear) at seven traditional spots around the community, but the ice that
  once held firm for months now cracks unpredictably. She spends afternoons teaching
  younger hunters, but increasingly finds herself saying "this ice behavior is new
  to me too."
documentation_type: adaptation_failure
environmental_stressor: Rapid Arctic sea ice loss and unpredictable freeze-thaw cycles
  making traditional ice-reading skills obsolete
family_situation: Widow whose husband died in 2041 when his snowmobile broke through
  ice that looked solid. Her adult son moved to Iqaluit for construction work after
  three failed hunting seasons. Her granddaughter visits summers but speaks mostly
  English now.
file_name: last_human.json
final_thought: Like the polar bears she's watched grow thin and desperate, swimming
  between ice floes that drift further apart each year, she realizes that all her
  ancestral wisdom - passed down through dozens of generations - has become obsolete
  in a single lifetime. The foundation of her world has literally melted away.
last_days_scenario: 'In late March 2043, Anyu sets out on what she knows will be her
  last traditional seal hunt. The ice forms three weeks later than when she was young,
  and breaks up a month earlier. She carries emergency GPS beacons now - something
  that would have shamed her grandfather. Halfway to the traditional hunting grounds,
  she hears the ice singing - the deep groaning that means it''s under stress. Her
  grandfather''s pick, which once told her everything about ice safety, now feels
  like a relic from another planet. She catches one small seal, but spends the return
  journey jumping between ice floes that shift and crack beneath her feet. Back home,
  she hangs up her hunting gear and tells her granddaughter over video call: "The
  ice doesn''t speak our language anymore."'
